Barack Obama to receive Nobel Peace Prize as fourth US president
US President Barack Obama arrives in Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth US president in history.
He will receive a diploma, medal and check for $1.4 million for, among other things, exceptional efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The White House chief will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife Michelle and be busy.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of the committee, which selected him from 172 people and 33 organizations in October.
The presidential couple are then scheduled to meet with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will receive it as america's fourth president, but only the third to win the award directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the Afghan war when accepting the award.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he realizes that he is accepting the award as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
He stepped up his war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, something none of his critics will forget to stress.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, diploma and cheque for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate them to charity, but he hasn't decided on a specific charity yet.
The busy schedule will then take the president and his wife to a banquet, which will include the Prime Minister and 250 other invited guests in addition to the King and Queen of Norway.
From the outset, Obama was more reticent about the price.
For example, he stated that he felt he did not fully deserve it.
He also reiterated several times that this is not just a prize for him, but for all those who strive for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said it was a "call to action" for him.
