USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical how, with the schoolboy efforts of Barack Obama, a president with a reputation for being the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor, whom he considered the stupidest, on the Afghan issue.
When he finally sweated out his eagerly awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it through a copy machine from Bush's Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate to use the title of bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration, "A New Way Forward."
Yet three years ago, he criticized Bush's idea to send fresh military reinforcements to civil war-torn Iraq as "an irresponsible and catastrophic decision in its afters."
But the months that followed showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field commanders, was the only possible and great success so much that there is no talk of Iraq in news reports today.
It did not improve Bush's reputation, but objectively left his successor far more grateful than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes for a repeat of the miracle.
Field commanders, notable Afghan Operation Commander General Stanley McCristal, who, despite subordination practices, harshly criticized the hesitant white house shooters, again asked him to increase his military contingent.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he cheated the general by 10,000 troops.
He was able to pull another 5,000 out of Europe, even though he had originally planned for at least 10.
The most problematic thing about Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in as little as 18 months and end the process within three years; the entire Obama doctrine raises more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a half-hearted increase will bear the same fruit as the advance in Iraq.
Despite the fratricicipation wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honoring the agreements.
The Afghan situation is marked by the opposite symptom - no one can be relied upon, and no agreements are being followed.
Under these conditions, Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing master every day, are difficult to prepare according to how it suits them.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain only a potemkin village, for which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely complex, given the missor of circumstances that make Pakistani and Iranian influences even more difficult.
Even building an "actionable state," which is a minimalist goal of the operation, doesn't seem very realistic.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is puzzled by his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of an explosion.
To believe that soldiers sent into the war for the purpose of "returning home soon" will cause a miracle here can only be a true romantic soul, untouched by reality.
Politically, setting a date for troop withdrawals is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will see this as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans' willingness to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is on the downs.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothoe of the Hindu Kukush.
Another factor capable of radically intervening in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and intensified sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the question arises before the United States whether to try to solve the problem with military force.
It will need to be answered just as, according to Obama, America is on the way to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any such solution will also mark a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only band-aid for Barack Obama is that there are three years left before the presidential election, and therefore there is still time for him to come up with another strategy if this proves to be a total flop.
