Czech discovery: a substance that works even on 'numb' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow down the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already gained immunity to drugs.
In some cases, this fact outweighs the fact that the compound does not act as strongly on a common variant of the virus as some already available drugs.
AIDS is not yet curable.
However, patients can significantly prolong life with a mixture of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Moreover, the incomplete suppression of the spread of the virus results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which the drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the University of The University of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that substances called metallocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metallocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all drugs used today and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new 'enhanced' compounds prepared based on knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metallocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is necessary for the life cycle of the virus.
Mature infectious viral particles would not have been created without HIV protease caused by HIV fission.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically altered.
Slightly weaker but more reliable
The effect of this series of HIV protease substances has been tested in a test tube as well as against its resistant (resistant) variants derived from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metallocarborans on a common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
