Moreover, many couples had to undergo sexist abortions, leading to an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, population officials have gradually been milder in their position on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they generally allowed exemptions -- including city dwellers, members of national minorities, and cases where men and women were only children -- and in 2007, they softened the diction of their hard-line slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University's Population Research Institute, said central government officials had previously debated more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners was an only child.
In June, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
