The UN Group outlined a plan to reduce emissions.
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by far-reachingly unruly attitudes and mutual reproach -- again focused Friday on releasing a document proposing ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden in the near term.
The text, which can provide a basis for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, highlights the remaining obstacles as well as illuminates the way forward.
But important progress has been seen in the negotiations that have taken place at the wrong time with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Created by an ad hoc UN working group, this text subtly states how much money rich countries should provide to the poor to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a variety of choices for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies so that they can limit their carbon output, and what should be the upper limit of global temperature rise that policymakers will still be able to tolerate.
This adds a lot of flexibility to the process, says John Coequyt, chief executive of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, made a 180-page text from the meeting to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as a "big picture."
It outlines the outlines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations could jointly limit their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by the year compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries could reduce their emissions to 15 to 30 percent during that period.
Together, the country would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union urgently discussed a promise friday to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries accept adaptation to climate change -- from managing floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Still, Friday introduced the same kind of verbal fireworks that prevailed in last week's talks.
Todd Stern, the US special envoy on climate issues, rejected a speech calling for binding limits on greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries compared to volunteering with major emerging economies if they were not financed by the developed world.
The shift signaled that the Obama administration had established a tougher line on China than bush administration officials just two years ago.
The United States will not accept the treaty without transferring major developing countries and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text was not sufficient to secure restrictions and should be vetted by external observers.
Stern made the comments an hour after China's Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei told america's chief climate negotiator that either a lack of "common sense" or "extraordinary irresponsibility" led earlier in the week to say that the United States would not help China financially to deal with global warming.
With the future of the economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, tug-of-war has erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current struggle is mostly about preserving individual economies rather than preserving the planet, between China and the United States over fulfilling their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that the world's two dozen most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take stronger action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers were fighting over who should bear the cost of reducing greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries have become much more aggressive in finding ways to prevent large issuers from being held accountable in their actions.
It's clearly a game about the new economic hegemony developing, said Ulate, who also serves as regional advisor on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for international conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the effects of climate change have indicated that they would like to continue pushing for a legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but most of the main participants said that a political agreement would be the best outcome of the talks.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page draft agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the advances by small island nations "have triggered political pressure on the entire political process" partly because they are now united and demanding action from growing economies such as China and India.
The negotiations created a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the remaining contentious issues before heads of government compete for an agreement.
High-ranking officials, such as India's Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China's Deputy Minister, disembarked from planes and ran through the lobby of the Bella Center to the closed doors of meetings and new conferences so that they could set out claims to be assessed next week.
The sheer size of the rally - with 13,000 people moving daily from and to the convention center, guitar-playing activists staging ironic spectacles at night about the countries they thought had sent them, and hand-to-hand hand-to-hand on paper rather than e-mail -- dominated by a challenge.
Intensity is only an over-the-top: almost all key ministers were present in Copenhagen and 60 heads of state earlier in the day.
We have reached high categories, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Deputy Minister for Global Policy for International Conservation of Nature.
The heavyweights are coming.
