Turkey's judiciary has disbanded for the Kurdish side, and this decision carries severe consequences.
Turkey's Constitutional Court on Friday ruled to abolish the country's main pro-Kurdish party. The decision immediately sparked protests in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision may greatly complicate the task of a government that seeks to lend a friendly hand to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it became "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Supreme Court President Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of negotiations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes needed to dissolve the party, Kiliç said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president, Ahmet Türk, and Aysola Tugluka, a member, are banned from participating in political life for five years.
At the same time, the judge announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr Türk and Mrs Tugluk and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP party has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 500).
The party leadership had already warned before the verdict that MPs would rather leave Parliament than act as politically affiliation MPs.
The decision is a continuation of a trial initiated in 2007 by The Court of Cassation Prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "orders" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is a legal political showcase for PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has no "basic connection" to the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court's verdict comes as the government shakes hands with the Kurdish community and offers a series of measures to strengthen their rights, attempting to curb Kurdish support for the PKK to end the conflict.
The DTP leadership confirmed that disbanding the party could lead to renewed tensions in the southeast of Anatolia, where many demonstrations against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan is being held in clashes with police have broken out in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of the justice decision, thousands of demonstrators have gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast that is predominantly Kurdish.
Police used tear gas grenades and water cannons, while demonstrators threw Molotov cocktails or fired stones from slingshots.
Also in Istanbul, about 100 people demonstrated.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said the justice decision would only "deepen despair."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (of the Kurds) by banning the party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We are against interference as a matter of principle.
It doesn't solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a complete blow to the democratic proposals initiated by the government, commented Ahmet Insel, a political scientist.
Of course, we can expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for one of the deadliest attacks in northern Turkey, killing seven soldiers three days earlier.
