However, such images and voices do not arise only in the mentally ill or in drug intoxication.
Our imagination is to blame: The same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings, or write novels make sure that the boundaries between dream, imagination and reality merge here and there.
Dreams altered state of consciousness can occur in various forms, at best we call them visions, at worst delusions.
But while the initiator and effect may vary, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New-Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic states of deliriousness, psychosis, and hallucinations can be inferred from similar processes.
Hallucinations or visions occur when the balance of neuronal transmitters of the brain - especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed, and interaction between different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often in schizophrenic psychosis.
