Ghosts are a terrible fact
About one percent of people get schizophrenia at least once in their lives, in psychiatric clinics it is the second most commonly treated disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, the afflictions usually can no longer distinguish the inner and outer worlds, they are put in an over-awakened state, which can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship illusions or the illusion of persecution.
Hearing voices is particularly prevalent - voices that order, comment or conduct dialogues.
Even optical hallucinations aren't uncommon.
The affected person is not able to distinguish the important from the unimportant, the brain cannot filter out disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, the psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
Perceptions of reality in psychosis are focused on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief medical officer of the Department of General Psychiatry at the University Clinic in Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has meaning directed at him.
At the same time, it gets into a passive role, becomes, as in a dream, over-emased by events and cannot actively shape them.
Therefore, schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is usually not possible with them, ghosts are a terrible fact, awakening is excluded.
Once in a lifetime to experience hallucinations
But, as Fuchss says, "the sensory and spatial structure of the reality one perceives in psychosis remains fundamentally preserved."
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience occurs in a real framework.
Scientists are still puzzled as to why exactly our brain does such cartwheings.
States of emergency can lead to a short-term relationship with reality for every person, fuchs says.
But not everyone develops into psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists assume that the affected people have minimal brain damage.
It is believed that at an early stage of development, neuronal maturation of the brain will be damaged, for example, by viral diseases of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains a puzzle how the neuronal system malfunctions, which has not manifested in any way for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis if there is a disposition to it.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis, since they interfere with the transmission system.
