Borderline state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our world concentrated too much on consciousness, the imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief medical officer of the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic at Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a severe, suffering disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - the miring is also an art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard explored the so-called oneiroid form of experiences, a special form of altered consciousness to a dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictitious dreams that the person concerned considers real and cannot even distinguish them retroactably from a alert state.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, such as patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis in full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and himself, perhaps by a continuing, complete inability to move, he replaces life-threatening real situations with his own imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, schmidt-degenhard says.
Kind of borderline state between dream and hallucination.
Because it is not possible to manage a situation in reality, there will be a change of worlds, but the real situation will become present in the imagination.
An intense form of sense support and sensory transfer in some unbearable situation that allows us humans to have our own ability to form, to transition into loss of consciousness in an instant.
