Zapatero predicts a 'quiet period' in the automotive industry.
Prime Minister José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero predicts that Spain's car industry, the state's main export sector, is in for a "quiet period."
In the Prime Minister's 2009 economic report, Zapatero summarised the measures that were put in place during the year to support the automotive sector.
"Without the Competitive Plan for the Automotive Sector, we would have had a state of abandonment today, the closure of some of our main manufacturing businesses," the Prime Minister said.
"Thanks to this plan and the desire of individual brands to continue to operate in Spain in this highly competitive sector, a period of calm is foreseen for the future for this industry, which is our main export sector," he added.
In this sense, it stated that the competitive plan, which forms part of the Integral Automotive Plan (PIA), had identified EUR 800 million for projects by 19 manufacturers and 137 subsidiaries that mobilised an investment of more than EUR 3 billion.
The Prime Minister explained that this investment is intended for the development of new models, for the modernisation of production and existing processes.
Zapatero also stressed the government's measures to support the request and mentioned the 2000E plan, which is implemented in cooperation with autonomous regions and car brands.
According to the president, the plan allowed the average emission level for new vehicles sold on the Spanish market to be reduced by 6% and ensured a "significant increase" in registrations, namely by "40% in November."
