75% of working mothers have maternity-related work problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and Careers of Spanish Women', carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
9,737 women aged 15 to 75 participated in the study, and the results are unequivocal: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market due to maternity.
The study highlights that at the beginning of cohabitation there are many differences of opinion on the number of children depending on whether they work or not, as well as the type of employment.
Women who do not work away from home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with a partner earlier, give birth to their first child earlier and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, cohabitation and motherhood, are putting off, and have fewer offspring.
"Women between the age of 35 and 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years after starting cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted a greater part of their lives to their stable employment and have therefore had to postpone cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, although less influence on the time of starting cohabitation with a partner", explains Margarita Delgado, researcher at CSIC.
Another factor influencing the age of women at the time of marriage and the anaroar of the offspring is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35 to 49 age group, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with basic education marry and give birth to their first child before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or high education do the opposite, preferring to get a stable job before marriage and the birth of their first child," delgado says.
