The auxiliary system for handbrakes is already mandatory equipment.
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock braking system, it will also be with esp stability control, auxiliary handbrake systems, all this will become mandatory equipment for European cars.
In fact, they are already part of the mandatory equipment for all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while others have a deadline for eliminating the shortage, which is February 2011.
The measure introduced in the EU aims to increase pedestrian protection, working in such a way as to help prevent many collisions.
The handbrake auxiliary system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects when the driver presses.
But it doesn't always manage to keep up that pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by car parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers who have an accident did not hit the brake before the collision, and half of them did not fully use the brake force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU alone, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1 100 pedestrian-related fatalities per year could be avoided.
Reducing this number will be even more significant-according to calculations, one in four accidents affecting people-after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) will catch obstacles and report them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help him increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if the collision cannot be avoided, the device will act as intensively as possible on the brake and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
